    <p>JavaScript</p>
{% endblock %}
{% block projectTechStack%}
    <p>Bootstrap</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block projectImage %}
    <img id="blog-board-individual-img" class="project-main-img" src="/assets/img/project-page-pics/space-invaders-screenshot.png">
{% endblock %}


{% block projectDescription %}
    <div id="objective-section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Objective</h2>
        <p>
            After learning about the JavaScript language in depth through a recent web-app development course, I decided
            to create a simple game to practice my "vanilla" JS and learn about commonly used design patterns. As someone
            who grew up playing arcade games on my family's DOS computer, Space Invaders seemed like a fitting choice.
            The end goal was to implement all common features of the game (multiple levels, high score, etc), with the
            bonus of being able to customize the setup by choosing the pictures for each onscreen character. If
            you're wondering where the inspiration for that came from, I started development on this shortly after the
            US election...
        </p>
    </div>
    <div id="implementation-section" class="description-section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Implementation</h2>
        <p>
            Probably the most valuable aspect of JavaScript that I learned through my web development course was closures.
            I'm only partially exaggerating when I say they opened up a whole new world of JS that I had never used.
            Closures were the key to a lot of design patterns I checked out, and the bread and butter of the module revealing
            pattern I ended up using for this project (more on that <a href="">here</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Presently the game has most key features except for multi level play. I also plan to connect the game to
            a Mongo DB on Heroku so players can track their high scores.
        </p>
    </div>
{% endblock %}

